title: Prep roundup, Oct. 13
text:
North Polk edges CMB 
ALLEMAN - Collins-Maxwell-Baxter suffered its sixth-consecutive loss Tuesday at the hands of North Polk. 
The Raiders were swept by the Comets to fall to 10-13 overall and 2-5 in the Heart of Iowa Conference. 
North Polk (24-11, 6-1) rallied for a 26-24 victory in the first set then took the second by a 25-17 margin. The Comets dominated the third set, prevailing by a 25-9 score to wrap up the match. 
“I am very happy with the way we played tonight,” CMB head coach Scott Ranck said. “I thought we played better tonight than we have for several matches. A lot of younger kids are playing now and they’re just kind of starting to get it all figured out.” 
Payge Jurgens had eight kills and one block, Bekah Pearson finished with five kills and Jordynn Wesselink produced four digs, three kills and one block for CMB. Sailor Hinegardner produced 11 digs, Kathleen Baldwin had 12 assists and four digs and Toni Spencer tacked on five digs for CMB. 
Hannah Becker led North Polk with 17 kills and seven digs. Gracie Harmeyer had 27 assists, Lexi Dvorak recorded seven kills, Riley Murphy put up five kills and two blocks and Carolyn Steffen went 14 of 14 serving with three aces. 
Nevada sweeps Roland-Story. 
Class 3A No. 4 Nevada defeated Roland-Story, 3-0 byt the scores of 25-14, 25-21 and 25-18 on Tuesday night. 
Alexa Whipple had eight kills for the Norse. 
GIRLS’ CROSS-COUNTRY 
Bombers and Kohut-Jackson take conference meet 
Ballard won the Raccoon River Conference meet with a score of 34, edging second-place Winterset by 15 points. The Bombers’ Abby Kohut-Jackson was the individual champ with a time of 18 minutes, 46 seconds. 
Ballard’s Abby Catus was sixth in 20:27, Summer McVivker seventh in 20:30. Ashley Meldrum ninth in 20:52 and Anna Zielke 11th in 21:05. 
BOYS’ CROSS-COUNTRY 
Ballard fourth at conference invite 
The Bombers placed fourth with a score of 102 at the Raccoon River Conference meet Tuesday. Winterset won the match with 33 points, just defeating Carlisle in second with 34. 
Ballard was paced by Owen Zunkel in 15th place with a time of 17:29. Bryce Snell was 17th in 17:34, Kegan Odden 22nd in 17:49, Ian Fletcher 23rd in 17:53 and Kaleb Wohlgemuth 25th in 18:02.
